      "Mary was a young woman living in Nazareth, betrothed to a carpenter named Joseph, when Luke's Gospel records that the angel Gabriel appeared to her and announced she would conceive a son by the Holy Spirit who would be called \"the Son of the Most High\" (Luke 1:26-38). Her response — \"I am the Lord's servant... may your word to me be fulfilled\" — is followed by a visit to her relative Elizabeth, during which Mary speaks the hymn of praise known as the Magnificat, celebrating God's favor toward the lowly (Luke 1:46-55).",
      "Joseph, learning of the pregnancy, initially planned to quietly end the engagement until an angel reassured him in a dream (Matthew 1:18-25). Mary traveled with Joseph to Bethlehem for a Roman census and gave birth to Jesus there, laying him in a manger because there was no room for them at the inn (Luke 2:1-7). At the child's presentation in the Jerusalem temple, an elderly man named Simeon blessed the family but warned Mary that \"a sword will pierce your own soul too,\" foreshadowing the grief she would later experience (Luke 2:22-35).",
