    id: "barnabas",
    name: "Barnabas",
    pronunciation: "BAR-nuh-bus",
    tier: "major",
    role: "Missionary and early church leader",
    summary: "A generous Cypriot Levite whose vouching for the newly converted Saul of Tarsus, and whose partnership on the first missionary journey, helped launch Paul's apostolic career before the two men split over a sharp disagreement.",
    lifeStory: [
      "Barnabas is introduced in Acts as Joseph, a Levite from Cyprus, whom the apostles nicknamed \"Barnabas,\" meaning \"son of encouragement.\" He sold a field he owned and laid the proceeds at the apostles' feet, an early example held up in Acts as a model of generosity within the Jerusalem community (Acts 4:36-37).",
      "When the newly converted Saul (Paul) arrived in Jerusalem, the other disciples were still afraid of him, remembering his role persecuting the church. It was Barnabas who took the risk of vouching for him, bringing him to the apostles and describing his Damascus road conversion (Acts 9:27). Later, when a mixed Jewish-Gentile church took root in Antioch, Barnabas was sent to investigate, and it was Barnabas who traveled to Tarsus to bring Saul in as a teacher there — the two spent a year building up that congregation together (Acts 11:22-26).",
      "The church at Antioch commissioned Barnabas and Saul as its first missionary team, and Acts 13-14 recounts their journey through Cyprus and Asia Minor together — at Lystra, the crowds were so astonished by a healing that they tried to hail Barnabas as Zeus and Paul as Hermes (Acts 14:12). By this point Paul had clearly become the primary spokesman, but the partnership held.",
      "That partnership broke over a specific, well-documented dispute. Preparing for a second journey, Barnabas wanted to bring along his cousin John Mark, who had abandoned them partway through the first trip; Paul refused. Acts records \"a sharp disagreement\" severe enough that the two separated, Barnabas taking Mark to Cyprus while Paul chose a new partner, Silas (Acts 15:36-41). Paul's letters confirm Barnabas remained an active, respected missionary in his own right afterward, though the two are never again recorded working side by side.",
    ],
    controversies: [
      "The split with Paul over whether to bring John Mark on the second missionary journey is recorded plainly in Acts 15:36-41 as a genuine falling-out between two church leaders, not a later legend.",
      "Galatians 2:11-13 reports that at Antioch, Barnabas — like Peter — began withdrawing from table fellowship with Gentile believers under pressure from a circumcision faction, prompting Paul to publicly confront Peter; Paul notes Barnabas was 'led astray' by the same hypocrisy.",
    ],
    occupation: "Landowner, then missionary and teacher",
    placesLived: "Native of Cyprus; active in Jerusalem, Antioch, and on missionary travels through Cyprus and Asia Minor.",
    noExtraBiblicalRecordNote: "A 2nd-century text called the Epistle of Barnabas circulated under his name and later traditions (the apocryphal Acts of Barnabas) describe his martyrdom in Cyprus, but neither is considered to have actually been written by him or to preserve reliable historical detail — they are pseudonymous and legendary rather than contemporary sources.",
    verses: [
      { reference: "Acts 4:36-37", note: "Introduced as a generous Levite from Cyprus" },
      { reference: "Acts 9:27", note: "Vouches for the newly converted Saul" },
      { reference: "Acts 13:1-3", note: "Sent out with Saul as the church's first missionaries" },
      { reference: "Acts 15:36-41", note: "Splits from Paul over John Mark" },
    ],
    sources: [{ label: "Encyclopaedia Britannica: Saint Barnabas", url: "https://www.britannica.com/biography/Saint-Barnabas" }],
