    id: "antonius-felix",
    name: "Antonius Felix",
    pronunciation: "an-TOE-nee-us FEE-lix",
    alternateNames: ["Felix"],
    tier: "significant",
    role: "Roman governor of Judea who imprisoned Paul for two years",
    summary: "A former slave who rose to become Roman procurator of Judea, and who kept Paul imprisoned at Caesarea for two years hoping for a bribe — a governor the Roman historian Tacitus described as ruling 'with the mind of a slave.'",
    lifeStory: [
      "Felix was unusual among Roman governors in that he had begun life as a slave; he and his brother Pallas were freedmen who rose to prominence through connections in the imperial household, eventually securing Felix the governorship of Judea around AD 52-58. He married Drusilla, a Jewish princess and daughter of Herod Agrippa I, having reportedly persuaded her to leave her previous husband.",
      "When Paul was arrested in Jerusalem and accused before the Sanhedrin of stirring up unrest, he was sent to Felix in Caesarea for trial. Felix heard the accusations from the Jewish leaders and Paul's own defense, then postponed a decision, keeping Paul in custody but with some freedom for friends to attend to his needs (Acts 24:1-23).",
      "Felix and Drusilla later sent for Paul privately to hear him speak about faith in Christ; when Paul reasoned about righteousness, self-control, and the coming judgment, Felix became alarmed and sent him away, saying he would call for him again when convenient. Acts is direct about his motive for the delay: 'he hoped that money would be given him by Paul' (Acts 24:26). Paul remained imprisoned for two full years until Felix was replaced by Porcius Festus, and, wanting to leave the Jewish leaders satisfied, Felix left Paul in custody rather than release him.",
    ],
    controversies: [
      "The Roman historian Tacitus offered a scathing verdict on Felix's governorship, writing that he 'wielded the power of a king with the mind of a slave' (Historiae 5.9) — a pointed jab given Felix's origins as a freedman — and describing his rule in Judea as marked by cruelty and corruption. This external Roman assessment lines up with Acts's own implication that Felix was angling for a bribe from Paul.",
    ],
    occupation: "Roman procurator (governor) of Judea",
