      "At the hearing, the accusations against Paul went unproven, and Festus, wanting to do the Jewish leaders a favor, asked Paul if he was willing to go to Jerusalem to be tried there instead. Paul, aware of the danger and asserting his rights as a Roman citizen, responded, 'I appeal to Caesar' (Acts 25:9-11) — a formal legal move that, once made, obligated Festus to send him to Rome.",
      "Before Paul's departure, Festus arranged the hearing before King Agrippa II and Bernice described elsewhere, partly because he needed a clearer account of the charges to include in his report to the emperor, admitting he found it strange to send a prisoner to Rome without specific charges to state (Acts 25:26-27). Josephus, writing later, describes Festus's tenure as comparatively brief but reasonably effective, noting he moved against banditry and unrest in the province more successfully than several of his predecessors and successors — though Festus died in office after only about two years.",
